                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           SPORT BRIFS
                                                Dravid to play   Ranji tie  Mumbai: Rahul Dravid is to straightaway plunge into domestic cricket after playing in the drawn second and final Test against England at Mohali.  The former India skipper is to represent Karnataka, led by Robin Uthappa, against Saurashtra in the four-day Ranji Trophy quarter final commencing at the Brabourne Stadium on Tuesday. ldquo;Rahul is to arrive here tomorrow, rdquo; said sources in the Karnataka team which practiced this afternoon at the Cricket Club of India.  Bucknor back  Calcutta: The International Cricket Council (ICC) on Tuesday appointed Steve Bucknor and Nigel Llong as umpires for the two-match Test series between Bangladesh and Sri Lanka, starting from Friday in Dhaka.   According to a release, Jeff Crowe will be the Match Referee.  Shiva wins   New Delhi: Shiva Keshavan claimed bronze in the Luge Asian Championships at Nagano, Japan. Keshavan on Monday clocked 1:44.155, three-tenth behind Ocuchi Takahisa of Japan (50.734) who bagged the gold.   Tania draws  New Delhi: Defending champion International Master Tania Sachdev settled for a draw against last seed Bhakti Kulkarni of Goa, helping Kruttika Nadig to secure the sole lead once again in the 35th Parsvnath National Women Chess Championship on Tuesday.  Natl A chess  Mangalore: Defending champion, PSPB rsquo;s Surya Sekhar Ganguly of Bengal and India rsquo;s youngest Grandmaster Parimarjan Negi are jointly leading with 4.5 points each at the end of seventh Round of the 46th National A Chess Championship on Tuesday. While Surya drew with Grandmaster Neelotpal Das in the 23rd move, Negi defeated the only Grandmaster from Karnataka, M S Thejkumar in 37 moves.   Chess meet  Calcutta: DBCA Boys A and Dabaru, with eight points each, were in joint lead after the Round II of All Bengal Team Chess Championship being organised by Dibyendu Barua Chess Academy on Tuesday. Half-a-point behind the leaders are CCA Rooks. Eastern Railway scored full points against DPS, Ruby Park, but dropped a point against Howrah District M.M. CCA.   Semis line-up  Calcutta: Arshdeep Tiwana booked a semi-final spot at the LG-Goodricke Eastern India Amateur golf tournament at the Royal Calcutta Golf Club, beating Gagan Verma. Arshdeep will face Karan Vasudeva, who beat Rahul Bajaj.   
